cs.IT, cs.NI, cs.SI, cs.MM, cs.COM

Reasoning: 
1. cs.IT (Information Theory) is the most likely category as the paper deals with power allocation schemes to achieve capacity in parallel channels, which is a fundamental problem in information theory. 
2. cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) is also likely as the paper discusses the practical use of the findings in evaluating the mutual information of example SIMO parallel channels using simulations as well as new measured ultrawideband channel data. 
3. cs.SI (Signal Processing) is another possible category as the paper deals with single-input multiple-output (SIMO) Nakagami-m fading subchannels, which is a signal processing problem. 
4. cs.MM (Multimedia) is a possible category as the paper deals with power allocation in parallel channels, which is relevant to multimedia communication systems. 
5. cs.COM (Computers and Society) is the least likely category as the paper does not deal with social or ethical issues related to computers and society.
